./docs/sprint-memos/7h-41-V6d-roadmap.codex.log:5143:   420	- 2026-04-27 [orchestration][parallel-write-fanout] **4-way parallel codex (2 write-mode worktrees + 2 readonly memos) is the right unit for one sprint when slices share a file surface; parent owns the conflict weave.** Sprint 7h-37 ran S1 (`cursor/smoke-multiprofile`) + S2 (`cursor/vault-smoke-vaultOneLogin`) write workers concurrently, both touching `scripts/smoke/smoke.py` and `keeper_sdk/core/diff.py`. The 5 conflict regions resolved cleanly under one rule: "PAM path = profile-aware (S1); vault path = S2 plumbed onto S1's `run_context.title_prefix`". Wall time: ~15min total (longest worker = S1 ~13min). Orchestrator time: ~25min (worker launch + poll + merge weave + push + cleanup). Throughput ROI vs serial: at least 2x because S2 + memos run while S1 churns through ruff/pytest/mypy. Pattern: worktree-per-slice + cite-rich prompt + worker self-pushes its branch + parent owns merge-with-rule. Anti-pattern: trying to merge a worker branch via `gh pr` when `gh` isn't installed — direct `git merge --no-ff` of `origin/<branch>` works and is faster.
